segments.text: I'm sitting in John Capo's beautiful living room looking out over the lake and chatting with John about his experiences as a student.
First question, why did you go to A&M?
I went because my brother was going to A&M at the time and
It made it easier and was probably the least expensive place I could find to go to school simply because we didn't have any money.
As far as you know, did you have a choice if you had wanted one?
Not really.
No, my brother would have injured me again.
He injured me many times being four years older than me.
He would have done it again.
Now, high school was where?
Waco High School.
Waco High School.
You visited the campus many times then before going down to enroll.
No, once.
Once.
What was your impression on that visit?
It was a little stark.
It was a little frightening because my background for a college campus was Baylor in Waco, which is gothic, beautiful, shady trees and so forth.
College Station wasn't like that in 1948.
Okay, so you enter in the fall of 1948.
Yes.
Describe how you got there, the trip, and what you took with you
when you went to enroll?
Who took you, how'd you?
Okay, my father was quite ill. As a matter of fact, he died two weeks after I left to go to A&M.
And so my brother took me to A&M.
He was a senior at the time, having been at A&M, gone into the Army, and then come back from the Army and was there as a senior at the time.
And so he took me, and I took one footlocker.
And that footlocker had a few changes of clothes and some toiletry and some bedding.
That was it.
Because I really didn't know what I was going to need.
He told me, this is what you need.
Take it.
Because in those days, freshmen were issued uniforms.
So precious little clothing went.
Can you recall your visual impression?
You referred to it briefly a while ago.
What was there?
What buildings were there then?
What was the campus?
The campus was the old system, now I believe the Jack Williams building.
The new area was new, which were the low three-story red brick dorms to the south.
To the north was the library and the petroleum engineering building, and behind it was the chemistry building and the academic building, and then a few dorms.
That was it.
The new, new area didn't exist, which was over by Savisa.
Savisa was there, of course.
However, that wasn't my freshman impression.
I was a freshman at Bryan Air Force Base.
Oh, good.
So my impression of A&M, when I went down to enroll as a freshman, was going into the Army.
I lived in a barracks where we all lived in a row.
Oh, good, good.
Because, see, we haven't had many of those.
All right, did you even...
Go to the campus?
Not as I came in to become a freshman, no.
I did not even go to the campus.
I had seen the campus before, but I went straight to Bryan Air Force Base.
Describe physically what there was.
Like any World War II base, you go through a gate with a guard on it.
They wanted to make sure we stayed in there once we got there.
Was this Guard Air Force?
No, no, no.
By then it was Texas A&M University.
I take part in the A&M College of Texas.
We drove down to what was an office building, again made out of wood, single story.
asphalt shingle painted white and across from it was the chapel.
Typical World War II, throw it up quickly, wooden Air Force base, Air Corps base.
Behind it was a long row of barracks buildings where we would ultimately live.
and some of them were converted into classrooms.
Behind that was the flight line with hangars, and parked on the ramp outside were old Stearman bi-wing training planes.
And that's what you saw when you wrote, when you came in.
All right.
This was not the first year for Fish out there, was it?
No, it was the second.
Second, all right.
And all freshmen were out there?
All freshmen went out there.
OK.
Describe how you then got checked in and so forth.
Do you remember?
Vaguely, because you're being herded like cattle.
And you go from here to there and sign here.
I believe that the registration occurred in what was the dining hall.

tables were set around for the various classes and if you're going to take this english you go to that table and find a class that you can get into and get into it and then you move to the next and the next and the next these that's my impression i'm sorry it's a long about how many freshmen
We were a pretty large class.
There were nearly 1,000 of us as freshmen.
And only freshmen?
Only freshmen.
Who was there to give leadership or orientation?
There were army officers and sergeants in the army out of the staff of the commandant.
tactical officers they are called, but we had both officers and sergeants.
We did not have upperclassmen at all.
So your class missed some of the campus hazing and so forth that might have, freshmen might have had.
They made up for it when we were sophomores, so it's okay.
Who were, do you remember the names of any of those key
active duty attack officers and so forth?
Who was Hayden Boatner?
General Hayden L. Boatner was commandant and after that nobody was in part.
Did you all see Boatner?
Oh yes.
Describe him and your impression of him.
Small man, rotund, heavy set.
Fixed face.
Not a, no smile, strictly business, pure business by the numbers.
One, two, three, welcome here.
You are going to be, these people are going to tell you what to do and when to do and how to do it and you better do what they say.
You took, do you remember how many hours you took?
I think I took 18.
And you took all your courses out there?
Yes.
Do you remember any of the faculty members by name who were out there?
Fish drill team was out there.
I think it originated because we were isolated.
That's what I've heard.
It originated there because of the isolation.
And I understand there was a fish band?
Yes.
Can you describe anything about either of those?
Who was in them?
Just the students.
Same thing.
No, but was it highly selected?
Was it hard to get in the...
It was not difficult to get in the band.
It was difficult to get on the fish drill team.
You had to be good.
And you had to want to do it and so forth.
But the band would take warm bodies because they were trying to put together a reasonable band.
As a band has always been, as far as I know, it was not a formal organization or an official organization.
It was...
done on your own time and because you enjoyed being in a band.
And it played for our parades out there.
And they were generally people that had been through music in high school and were pretty good.
They were good.
We did a good job.
We did go to the campus for football games and the Fish Band marched independently.
Really?
About how big was it?
The number one?
Very big.
No, I think 40, 50, small, small.
All right, let's talk about that when you all went to the campus.
About how often did you go to the campus?
For a football game in the fall.
It wasn't every weekend either.
But you went to each football game?
Yes.
Okay, each home game.
What else?
If buses came, picked you up, you went in, you marched in, you stood where the freshmen stood.
You were freshmen.
It gave the upperclassmen a chance to look at you and to harass you a little bit.
And at the end of the game, you were picked up and taken back to the airport base.
All right.
So did you all go for dances or concerts or chapel?
No, we had a chapel out there.
So football games?
That's about the only thing we got in the fall.
That's about the only thing that I can recall that we... Did we go for any other time?
We, of course, were off on weekends, and because I had a brother over there, I would go on other weekends simply because my brother was there.
But you didn't go over there and spend the night?
Oh, no.
How would...
If you wanted to go, you or any of your buddies wanted to go, almost no one had a car, how did you get there?
They ran buses.
There were buses that went back and forth.
You had to get back on that last bus.
Now my brother had a car and
Sometimes, if he was in a good mood, he'd bring me back.
Other than that, he was a senior dealing with the pressure.
The faculty that taught out at the air base lived out there?
Or did they?
I don't think so.
I don't think so.
The base housing, as I recall, was not occupied.
You lived in a barracks?
Classic barracks.
No, you didn't have a room?
No.
There was a long single, the barrack was a long single room with double deck bunk stacked down the middle, a heater at each end and you were, the bunks were stacked between the two heaters.
Your bunk mate, you had a desk on one end of your bunk and he had a desk on the floor on the other, a desk and chair.
and that was your study place, and that was your bunk, so you had a little strip of floor about five feet wide.
Had people walking behind you while you're trying to study up and down.
Entrance hall and storage area on the front, and a toilet on the rear.
Showers, et cetera, everything on the rear of the building.
Where did you hang your clothing?
We have a little locker beside your desk.
Small, small locker beside your desk.
Your foot locker went under the bed?
Went at the foot of the bed, one on each end.
See, in the military configuration of a pure barracks,
they would have had two beds foot to foot in a wide aisle.
By running only one bed width, there was a good amount of space on the outside.
Now, since it was all freshmen, I'm assuming y'all didn't play many tricks on another student.
No more than the normal.
But I mean, you didn't hide somebody's footlocker.
there were no drown outs and so forth?
Oh yeah, there were drown outs, sure.
You know, just to hassle somebody.
A great recreation was to cut across the air field to the bridge.
Brazos County was dry and so you could, if you hiked across the air base,
and didn't follow the highway.
It was only about three miles to the bridge, and there was, of course, liquor and beer across the bridge.
The big deal was to go over and get the beer and drink it back.
Did any of those places have a name?
I'm sure they did.
But you don't remember?
No.
I'm sure they had a name.
There had been gambling there during the war.
Was there any gambling available then?
Not that I know of.
Okay.
And there had been a house of ill repute over there, reputed during the war.
Describe for me a typical class day routine.
Got up at what time, did what, under what sequence?
You got up in the morning early.
You assembled on the street in front of the barracks.
And the role was called wearing the uniform of the day, whatever it may have been.
Whatever the uniform of the day was, you assembled in front of the building in the uniform of the day.
And you marched to the dining hall for breakfast.
After eating, you found your way to wherever you were to be next, either back to your barracks or to your first class, as the case may be.
It was then typical university.
During the day, you went from class to class.
If you had time off, you went back to the barracks or the gymnasium was active and open.
Pick up football games and baseball games were always going on.
Did you fall in and march to midday meal?
No.
No, because you were quite scattered out and there wasn't time.
There wasn't time.
Everybody ate within one hour and you could not get assembled.
do the marching.
You did at night.
You marched back at night.
Again, you reassembled for the evening meeting.
And then again, you were on your own.
We had a lights out.
And I don't remember the time.
10 or 10.30 was early, which meant you had to get your studying done.
And they were checking on you to make sure you had your head in focus.
By and large, you studied at your desk.
At your desk.
Was there a library of any sort, any kind of a building?
No.
If you needed something from the library, you determined what it was, and it was brought to you from the campus.
Where were the classes held?
They were held in what had been
I suppose office buildings and some of the barracks converted into classes.
There was still in the, because the airplanes were stored there, the Air Force still had storage stuff around, so really the university did not occupy every building on the base.
Do you remember any classes that anyone wanted to take that were not available?
No, I don't think they were offered.
In those days, you had a pretty packed freshman course.
If you are going to be a freshman and you're going for a science degree, these are the courses that you will take as a freshman.
If you're going for an arts degree, these are the courses that you will take as a freshman.
But there were freshman courses that engineering majors, science majors, and so on?
Yes.
What was your major?
Mine was science.
I went for engineering.
Engineering, so I was after science.
So from day one, that was your goal.
Let's see.
Okay, then let's say you wanted to take a nap in the middle of the afternoon.
Was that even possible in that barracks?
Well, you learn to.
Yeah, people are coming in hollering and throwing their books down and so forth, but you could do the best you can, but there was no guarantee of peace, no.
All right, then tell me what y'all, now you had Saturday morning classes.
Let's say it's now noon Saturday.
What would have been a weekend of fun and relaxation?
What did y'all do on Saturday afternoon, night, and Sunday?
That's usually when you would see pickup sports around.
Go to town, go to a movie.
Go to town meant to do that?
Right.
Debride, not College Station.
How did you get to work?
Again, buses ran.
A few people had cars, except so many of my friends did.
But a movie, a few sports, that's pretty much, it was bare bones.
Now, on Saturday night, was there a bed check?
Yes.
Yes.
Sunday, were there religious services out there?
There was usually a religious service at the chapel.
You were free to go to town to any church you wanted to go to.
Or you were free not to go to church, as you may see fit.
I would guess that most of the freshmen, the majority of them, slept until noon.
It was a chance to get some sleep, and the vast majority did.
So that's the only day that there wasn't a morning fallout.
Yes, Sunday.
How were you all, on a weekday, how were you awakened?
By what method?
Well, the bugle,
recording that or it was at all army bases through loudspeakers all over everywhere and would wake the dead with its volume was there.
You were usually up before that because you had a limited number of people could take a shower at a time.
A limited number could shave at a time.
And so if you were smart, you were probably up before that, particularly if you have an 8 o'clock class and can't come back after breakfast.
If you can't come back to the dorm, you're up long before that vehicle.
Who was it that informed you all, prepared you for any traditions and slang and so forth?
Was that done that year?
Not really.
Not really.
There was some of it that went along.
But no, not really.
You picked up a little bit from the upperclassmen when you were on campus for football afternoons.
You picked a little bit up then.
But no, not really.
So you didn't know Agus Lane then for food yet?
Yeah, you learned all of that.
I don't remember how, whether it was just natural
Because y'all wouldn't have whipped out to another fish.
No, not really.
We did insist when you were with a group, you met everybody in the group, but not the formal thing.
Not the standard attention.
You must have been organized as companies.
And so a fellow freshman was the company
Yes.
Leader?
There would be a company commander and he was usually the, he was selected by the staff, by the tactical officer.
What company were you in?
I wish you hadn't asked me that.
I have the slightest notion.
Did the company have anything to do with the branch
in which you hoped to be?
They were broken down into Army and Air Force.
Those were the only two divisions.
And that was a selection you could make coming here.
See, I haven't run into many people who were out there.
That's why I'm quizzing you.
We were pretty stark and pretty minimal.
And a whole lot of people didn't stay.
It just wasn't what a college experience should be.
It was not.
Of the approximately 1,000 who started,
About how many were back as sophomores?
Less than half.
Less than half.
A lot before Christmas.
A lot didn't come back after Christmas.
And even more didn't come back.
All right.
You came to campus for football games.
What about midnight Yale practice?
No.
We did Yale practice out there.
Basketball games?
In the spring.
That was an option, but there were really too many.
You know, basketball games go on every day of the week, and there were really too many, and the pressure was too great with transportation tonight.
Did you all come for final review?
Yes.
Describe what it was like to be in final review, and you're going to become no longer a freshman.
Again, we marched as our own units, and it was...
if you will, just another parade because we marched as our own units.
So it was really, you know, final review is a big deal to us, but it's just another damn parade.
And you were on the drill field?
On where the MSC now.
That was the only place.
But it was then, it had nothing on the south side of it, did it?
No, no.
They were clearing and preparing to build the Student Center.
So that was the beginning of construction of the Student Center.
I think we actually got into the Student Center during my sophomore year.
I think that somewhere in there we got into the Student Center.
But I remember the construction.
What is your memory of the quality of food served out at the Air Base?
You know, I never complained about the food.
It was good food.
It was well prepared.
I had no complaints.
I came from a background where sometimes we had one meal a day.
So three meals a day, I didn't eat anything.
It didn't matter.
And you all did not, I believe you said you did not have any of the games, the rituals out there.
No.
All of that came in the sophomore year and was an intense thing.
Okay, now let's move to that sophomore year.
You come to the campus and you're on the campus.
Where did you live as a sophomore?
Over in what is known as the new area.
The low red brick buildings, dorms one through 12.
And you were in?
I was in dorm five.
What after?
E Battery Field Artillery.
Did it have a nickname?
No.
Nicknames, I think, came later.
Those are later innovations.
What did the juniors and seniors do to y'all that was kind of initiation-like?
Treated us like freshmen are treated today.
So you had to clean some upperclassmen's room?
Yes, but we now were a little bit more mature.
You would do it, but you wouldn't take a whole lot.
You would take a lot off of an upperclassman.
But if one got a little bit carried away, he would get it back, usually in spades.
Describe that part.
What might happen to a junior or senior who became abusive?
Well, his room could disappear and no one would tell him where it was and everything in it.
And where would it?
Into the steam tunnels.
He usually knew where to go look for it.
But it's a hard job to haul your bed and your mattress and your books when they've been scattered through the steam tunnels.
There's a lot of miles, a lot not miles, but there's hundreds of yards of steam tunnels under the ground there.
And he could come back to his room and there would be nothing there.
And that would usually deliver him, sometimes he would get mean to the entire class.
And so once we took a guy,
almost to the airport and tied him to a tree.
And nobody had any idea what happened to him.
It was about 20 hours before they found him.
Then he didn't bother us anymore.
And he knew who it was?
Of course.
It was very important that he know who did it.
Other good bull?
Oh my.
Did y'all ever put anything in anyone's room that exploded?
Yes, we did all of those things.
Firecrackers inside of a bag of flour, which will multiply its energy by a thousand times.
You know, just like a grain elevator explosion.
You just need a small firecracker and a paper bag of flour, and that's a multiplication many times over the power of the firecracker.
Water.
always water every night somebody is going to get it.
And it's usually an upperclassman.
It's usually that junior or senior that's going to get it, because the sophomore is the one who feels abused.
And somebody's going to pay one way or another.
In general, were these pranks played on somebody that had done this?
Yes.
Yes.
It was in retribution, without question.
They were generally retribution.
A little bit of difference.
By Thanksgiving, the bullshit was over.
After you came back from Thanksgiving, it was generally over.
By the time you come back from Christmas, you're just another
member of the outfit.
And the upperclassmen behaved that way?
Yes, yes, the upperclassmen treated you that way.
By the time you came back at Christmas, it was all over with.

Oh, you got a frog or two in that came in at mid-semester, and so you had to, they would hassle him a little bit, and he would be totally not understanding, why me, God, you know, and all of these other people.
Normally, frogs came from what students?
Well, people that had graduated from high school in January or in December, as the case may be, and entered as a freshman at mid-semester.
Right, but now there were frogs who transferred from other schools.
Yes, yes.
That could happen, too.
Was anyone from JTAC or NTAC?
Not in my outfit.
All right.
Oh, I was going to ask if they were treated differently from this mid-semester high school grade.
No, they would have had the same hassle.
Now, it didn't last long, 30, 45 days, because everybody's burned out and tired of it.
It's spring, and we're worn out with that stuff.
So it's a little flurry, and then it's gone.
All right.
Describe the child fall routine.
for sophomore Duncan Collin?
You're talking about in September.
In September, not much different than a freshman would experience today.
But again, by November, they're no different than a sophomore today.
The senior and junior eats first, and then you eat.
But no more table hassling.
But you were, for the first few months, you were to serve them?
Yeah, you pretty much sat at attention and ate when you were told to eat.
And if you were told not to eat, you didn't eat.
And all of those good things.
The good jobs, waiting tables, usually went to the juniors and seniors.
Those were the best jobs.
Now, those were also good juniors and seniors.
who made sure that nobody went without food.
If you stayed at that table, they'd bring you out a complete table serving
